Introduction

This R Markdown document demonstrates my ability to use models for data analysis using a dataset on diamond prices.

What affects diamond prices?

In this report, we examine what factors predict the price of a diamond.

Carat affects price

## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = price ~ carat, data = diamonds)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -18585.3   -804.8    -18.9    537.4  12731.7 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -2256.36      13.06  -172.8   <2e-16 ***
## carat        7756.43      14.07   551.4   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1549 on 53938 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8493, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8493 
## F-statistic: 3.041e+05 on 1 and 53938 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Based on a scatter plot of carat and price, as carat increases, the price also increases. The model suggests that for every additional carat, the price rises significantly.

The model shows that in addition to carat, cut, color, and clarity all influence diamond prices. Higher-quality cuts and clearer diamonds tend to be more expensive.
